                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/13/2003&nbsp;: 1:38:54 PM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /> Back in those days, it was not uncommon for someone to spend 20+ hours at a camp and not walk out with anything because someone who did not need the loot won the random rolls. What's more, many people did not have the time or interest to go /auction in East Commons for hours on ends in order to sell loot they cannot use. Thus, people eventually got tired of having /random decide their fate. They implemented the NGB system to make sure that people of a certain class would get the loot they needed the fastest and to prevent people of another class to price-gouge in Ecommons. This is especially appealing when considered alongside camps such as the frenzied camp in Lower Guk - no one liked seeing a caster walk off with a FBSS while the monk who needed the item had to wait another 10+ hours for it to drop. People like that *were* considered greedy bastards because they would turn around and sell the loot for a much higher rate to people who had the willingness and time to go auction in Ecommons and then come back and try to get another FBSS. The key thing here is that NGB is assumed to be the fastest way through which people may attain the loot they needed - back then, selling/trading was DIFFICULT and often not possible for many people, so the fastest and most reliable way to obtain loot is to get into a NGB group and have a priority list - e.g. the person who was here the longest gets the first FBSS, person who came after him gets the second, and so on. <br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Right NBG was formed because at that time the bazaar didnt exist.<br /><br />You couldnt just take 2 min to place an item on a trader, set that price and go to work.. then come back with 50k and type /bazaar and spend it getting 2 upgrades... you couldnt do it..<br /><br />Now you can.<br /><br />Selling and buying is very easy now.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"><br />There is a huge diffrence between complaining abotu someone getting item XXX instead of you, and trying to talk on a messageboard about why you think a system is unfair and should be changed.<br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />My problem with this statement is that you seem to think that because you don't like a system that that system needs changed, while I would argue that you have every right to not take part in that system, or create a system that you like better. The EQ gods didn't legislate the rules about how loot would be distributed in game.<br /><hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br />So I dont have a right to talk about why I think a system is unfair?<br />So I dont have the right to say I think a system needs to be changed?<br /><br />It's not like i'm forceing you to stop useing NBG if you want to use it.. I'm just saying why I think it's unfair on a message board that leaves people free to ignore or respond as they wish.</span></font></td>
