              <tr>
                <td bgcolor="#3C4884" valign="top"
 nowrap><b><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2">Etadanik Mistmorgue</font></b></td>
                <td bgcolor="#3C4884" valign="top"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/13/2003&nbsp;: 12:33:40 PM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> Laeelin, in EQ there is such a thing as "being born poor."  It doesn't work quite like in RL, however.  For instance, let's say that a level 65 necro in Time gear with 500k+ pp starts a twink.  Obviously, this twink is far more "fortunate" than anyone of the same level.  Now consider someone who just started EQ and has exactly jack.  His character is obviously far "poorer" than the twink.<br /><br />Now you could, of course, argue that because you put in more time on your level 65 necro your twink is better, but how is that different than someone claiming that their parents put more time into their businesses and thus that's why they have more money? It's the same principle - people, like characters, are not born equal.  Our relations are not the same - the person who just started EQ has no guild and no friends to twink him, but you and I do.<br /><br />As mentioned, NBG is not a *WAY* to be "nice" to people - it's a SYSTEM.  Of course it would be "nice" of a person to win a roll and still let his loot be given to the person who need it the most, but that assumes a certain degree of faith in human nature that does not typically exist.  NGB, like randoming, is a way of balancing equality of opportunity with overall (economic) equality.  Friends and generous people don't *NEED* such a system to distribute loot.  It's the people who are NOT friends and who are NOT generous that require such a system to govern them.<br /><br />With that overall stance stated, let me respond to a few of your points:<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">In EQ you dont have money only if you chose not to make it a priority... A level 65 with poor gear, chose to be in that situation.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />So? It's the same as in RL - people who are on welfare can be "argued" to have CHOSEN to be in that situation by not going to school, not working hard, etc.  Of course, there's also the other side of it: not being able to go to school, not being able to work hard, etc.  But the same applies to EQ - what if the player CAN'T play much.  What if he CAN'T join a guild? What if he IS anti-social and don't have many friends? Are you going to hold that against him as you would hold the supposed "disabilities" of a poor person in RL against him? For each argument there is a counter-argument.  The player who couldn't play that much could've played more.  The person who didn't have enough money for a college education could've self-taught himself.  Either way, however, we're talking excuses, not actualities.  We can only deal in the present, not the past.  We can't change the fact that so_and_so did not play that much in the past and is now suffering for it, just as we can't change the fact that so_and_so in RL didn't get a college education and now can't find a job.  But are you really going to go ahead and tell them that they screwed themselves and it's their fault?<br /><br />That's not how welfare in RL works.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">They could have the money, but instead chose not to... there is nothing wrong with that choice, except when everyone else is expected to hand that gear to them.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />Again, same issue in RL.  What *do* you say to people on welfare who *could've* been college-educated hard-working citizens? Do you tell them to screw off or do you help them? This is the difference between being compassionate and being fair.  A "fair" system would say to those people - you screwed yourselves, too bad.  A compassionate system would help them despite the fact that they screwed up.<br /><br /><blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">Granted that it's not normally going to actually be said like that, but if players 1-4 would think to suggest that everyone should have a fair chance for it they will be thought of as loot hungry jerks.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />For all this theoreticaly argument, I should bring up some practical reasons why NGB was implemented in the first place.  See, in the old days of EQ, the bazaar did not exist and each class had certain pieces of gear that would SIGNIFICANTLY improve them and which they worked for.  Back in those days, it was not uncommon for someone to spend 20+ hours at a camp and not walk out with anything because someone who did not need the loot won the random rolls.  What's more, many people did not have the time or interest to go /auction in East Commons for hours on ends in order to sell loot they cannot use.  Thus, people eventually got tired of having /random decide their fate.  They implemented the NGB system to make sure that people of a certain class would get the loot they needed the fastest and to prevent people of another class to price-gouge in Ecommons.  This is especially appealing when considered alongside camps such as the frenzied camp in Lower Guk - no one liked seeing a caster walk off with a FBSS while the monk who needed the item had to wait another 10+ hours for it to drop.  People like that *were* considered greedy bastards because they would turn around and sell the loot for a much higher rate to people who had the willingness and time to go auction in Ecommons and then come back and try to get another FBSS.  The key thing here is that NGB is assumed to be the fastest way through which people may attain the loot they needed - back then, selling/trading was DIFFICULT and often not possible for many people, so the fastest and most reliable way to obtain loot is to get into a NGB group and have a priority list - e.g. the person who was here the longest gets the first FBSS, person who came after him gets the second, and so on. (this had problems, obviously, with people not wanting to be sixth on a list but with perma-camped camps such as frenzied in lguk it was the only way)<br /><br />BTW, just out of curiousity, if raid items were NOT nodrop, would you support a DKP system for a raiding guild wherein any class could bid on anything, Laeelin, even if they couldn't use the item?<br /><br /><br /></span></font></td>
              </tr>
