                <td bgcolor="#37437B" valign="top"><font color="white" face="verdana" size="2"><small>Posted&nbsp;-&nbsp;12/13/2003&nbsp;: 12:31:25 PM</small><hr size="1"><span class="spnMessageText"> <br />Few points..<br /><br />NBG is just one option for loot, in fact you have every <b>Freedom </b>to <b>choose</b> how your group will distribute loot..<br /><br />NBG <br />Ladder<br />Random<br />3pp/FS (ok ok, that was a joke)<br /><br />the <i>fairness </i>comes by way of your freedom to democratically come to an agreement on how the group <b>chooses </b>to distribute loot. You can draw a comparison between NBG and Communism (in a mechanical sense) but you have freely choosen the method for distributing loot and you can freely leave that group or system whenever you choose.<br /><br />If you choose to give up your basic Norrathian right to have a say in the system of loot distribution you take part in, then you have nobody to blame but <u>YOURSELF</u>, not the unfairness of the system for loot distribution that you recieve by default.<br /><br />My opinion is this..<br /><br />The more options for loot distribution the better, your power lies in your freedom to choose what system is best for you.<br /><br /><br /><br /><br /> <blockquote id="quote"><font size="2" face="arial" id="quote">quote:<hr height="1" noshade id="quote">There is a huge diffrence between complaining abotu someone getting item XXX instead of you, and trying to talk on a messageboard about why you think a system is unfair and should be changed.<hr height="1" noshade id="quote"></blockquote id="quote"></font id="quote"><br /><br />My problem with this statement is  that you seem to think that because you don't like a system that that system needs changed, while I would argue that you have every right to not take part in that system, or create a system that you like better. The EQ gods didn't legislate the rules about how loot would be distributed in game.</span></font></td>
